body:
Hi there!

I found what seems to be a bug related to having many adders in parallel, causing a segmentation fault during the first eval.

Here is the extremely basic testbench.
```
#include "Vtop.h"
#include "verilated.h"

#include <iostream>

typedef Vtop Module;

int main(int argc, char **argv, char **env) {

  Verilated::commandArgs(argc, argv);
  Verilated::traceEverOn(0);

  Module *my_module = new Module;
  my_module->eval();

  std::cout << "Testbench complete!" << std::endl;
  delete my_module;
  exit(0);
}
```

[Here](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/files/13238823/top.zip) is the source file.

The command that I used is
```
verilator --cc --exe --build ../tb.cc top.sv && ./obj_dir/Vtop
```

I'm using `Verilator 5.018 2023-10-30 rev v5.004-74-g41e5f6b7d`. I also got the same with `v5.016`, and working with Ubuntu 22.04 and `g++ 9.4.0`.

The segmentation fault is not completely deterministic, you may have to run it a couple of times to see it.

May you have any difficulty to reproduce, I can produce a Docker image to help.

Thanks!
Flavien
